181
00:24:54,878 --> 00:25:01,929
So not only do I say to myself, flower, I have a feeling of pleasantness, contentment, joy when I see a beautiful flower.

182
00:25:03,111 --> 00:25:05,934
Now, at that point, that's what happens to the Buddha.

183
00:25:06,154 --> 00:25:09,179
There's no distinction there between us and somebody who's liberated.

184
00:25:09,539 --> 00:25:11,982
But then something kicks in which says, I want that.

185
00:25:13,734 --> 00:25:24,183
and the first thing comes want want there's that there's something else comes into the equation that wants the flower and then there comes the identity I wanted

186
00:25:24,703 --> 00:25:49,529
so it's in the reverse of our language I want I scream is actually I scream want I that's how it happens psychologically and at that point of identification you see the next moment is very difficult to stop because psychically it's very empowered and that moment is the grasping of the flower and ripping it off and running away with it and that action is the becoming

187
00:25:49,509 --> 00:25:58,238
So, becoming that action is the same as the empowerment of will, is the same as kamma, is the same as an action.

188
00:26:00,242 --> 00:26:09,053
So these three words really are all pointing to the same thing, will, how we use the will, how you actually empower something.

189
00:26:09,093 --> 00:26:20,807
Now this is really very important to understand because don't confuse an idea which is laced with wanting, that we call a desire or a craving, with an act of kama.

190
00:26:20,846 --> 00:26:22,909
Nothing's happened, you see.

191
00:26:23,040 --> 00:26:47,157
so if you for instance walk into this kitchen and you think I'll have a cup of tea that's still at the level of just desire but as soon as you move even a nanometer of a finger towards the pot you're empowering that desire and in empowering that desire you're reinforcing your conditioning

192
00:26:48,843 --> 00:26:54,869
So the will is the engine or the empowerment of something.

193
00:26:55,576 --> 00:27:25,566
the kamma refers to the act that has been done and the bhāva refers to the self that continues its self-existence through this action every time it does something it says oh it's me me again I've done that so I must exist so those three things meld together in any action whether we are thinking or whether we're speaking or whether we're doing and in the world

194
00:27:26,338 --> 00:27:27,361
We're always acting.

195
00:27:27,480 --> 00:27:31,568
I mean, it's only when you sleep that you're not actually acting in some way.

196
00:27:32,109 --> 00:27:33,512
And the same can be said of the Buddha.

197
00:27:33,732 --> 00:27:38,362
So the Buddha woke up and he thought, well, it's time to do a bit of meditation.

198
00:27:39,083 --> 00:27:42,048
He did it for his own benefit, he said, and for the benefit of others.

199
00:27:42,088 --> 00:27:43,250
That's a good example.

200
00:27:43,500 --> 00:27:48,828
And then he thought, well, I'm a bit hungry now, so he'd get his bowl together and go off on Pindapad.

201
00:27:48,869 --> 00:27:52,335
Somebody would stop him on the way and say, how are you doing, Bhagavan?

202
00:27:52,494 --> 00:27:54,699
And he'd say, oh, I'm doing fine, how are you?

203
00:27:55,519 --> 00:28:00,288
Little pleasantries, he wasn't above the ordinary little pleasantries of life.

204
00:28:01,148 --> 00:28:06,396
On his alms round, people might ask him in and have a chat with him about the Dharma or something.

205
00:28:06,657 --> 00:28:10,503
So he's acting perfectly normal in the world,

206
00:28:10,483 --> 00:28:20,805
in a sense, like we do, but somehow we end up suffering, or we end up unsatisfied, or we end up, you know, unfortunate.

207
00:28:21,266 --> 00:28:30,805
So there's a special, the Abhidhamma tried to create a new word to describe the actions of a Buddha, and they came up with this word, kriya, which means sort of functional.

208
00:28:31,897 --> 00:28:44,372
And what they're trying to point to is the fact that although the Buddha was making decisions, although he was acting, there was no perpetuation of this delusion of I, this self, you see, this self.

209
00:28:44,893 --> 00:28:58,969
Now, we were talking yesterday about how we can come out of these levels of self, the body self, the emotional self, the thought self, into just this quite distinct feeling of a self-awareness, see?

210
00:28:59,589 --> 00:29:00,471
And it's

211
00:29:00,451 --> 00:29:24,805
The association with that, of course, when it dives into these other parts of our becoming or existence or something, as it dives into the thought life and emotions and whatnot, it manifests through that, this self manifests as somebody who speaks, somebody who feels, somebody who does.

212
00:29:26,067 --> 00:29:41,577
So that process there is the core of the karma that the Buddha's talking about when he's talking about that which is going to liberate us from suffering or otherwise.

213
00:29:42,384 --> 00:29:49,258
And all he says is, if you do something harmful to others or to yourself, harm will come of it.

214
00:29:49,778 --> 00:29:51,321
And good, good will come of it.

215
00:29:51,682 --> 00:29:56,832
Now, as we say, on the outside of things, it doesn't often turn out that way.

216
00:29:56,872 --> 00:29:58,695
You do something good and somebody hates you for it.

217
00:29:59,436 --> 00:30:01,601
You do something bad and you get away with it.

218
00:30:02,241 --> 00:30:04,686
But internally, it's not possible.

219
00:30:05,047 --> 00:30:05,929
That's the point.

220
00:30:06,449 --> 00:30:31,443
internally when we do something unwholesome it creates an unwholesome habit within us which you know creates a turbulence and often finds its way out in speech in actions and eventually of course it does you do get some comeback i mean if you're an angry sort of person you know in the end you do begin to wonder why nobody's calling around and nobody makes a phone call

221
00:30:32,150 --> 00:30:40,347
Whereas, you know, if you've got onto the idea that, well, if you're very open and kind and generous, people sort of hang around, you think, oh, that's a good thing, you see.

222
00:30:40,648 --> 00:30:47,323
Of course, it becomes a big ego thing then, but at least it tends to be a bit happier than being a grump.

223
00:30:48,990 --> 00:30:54,423
So internally though, we're creating this internal world.

224
00:30:54,703 --> 00:30:57,951
And that's exactly what we come across when we sit in meditation.

225
00:30:57,971 --> 00:30:58,953
This is our creation.

226
00:30:59,394 --> 00:31:03,364
Nobody's created the inner world for us.

227
00:31:03,443 --> 00:31:06,190
This has all been done by our act of will.

228
00:31:06,170 --> 00:31:08,192
Now, of course, there are catalysts.

229
00:31:08,473 --> 00:31:18,048
If you happen to be with people who are coarse and vile and all that sort of stuff, it's very difficult to maintain a purity of mind.

230
00:31:18,490 --> 00:31:22,676
But if you're with people who are good, generally speaking, then it's easier.

231
00:31:22,656 --> 00:31:38,843
All the surroundings, all the culture that we're in, people we meet, the jobs we do, all that, sure, they're there as catalysts but it's always an internal process which is actually creating this internal psychology.

232
00:31:39,228 --> 00:31:48,142
And that's, you know, at first that might come as a bit of a disappointment because it's always nice to blame somebody else for our problems, you know, and try and get compensation.

233
00:31:48,682 --> 00:32:00,642
But there's also a liberation there because obviously if my happiness is dependent on you, fundamentally dependent on you, and you're making me unhappy, then I don't have much of a choice.

234
00:32:00,682 --> 00:32:01,624
I've just got to get rid of you.

235
00:32:02,161 --> 00:32:04,326
and I've got to get rid of anybody whom I don't like.

236
00:32:05,128 --> 00:32:12,047
But if I am the one who's creating my own unhappiness, then this course means that it's just me I've got to work with.

237
00:32:12,267 --> 00:32:17,942
It's just me that I have to find the answer within.

238
00:32:17,922 --> 00:32:32,403
and that comes as a sort of liberation really because it liberates me from the world out there and throws me back into myself and makes me want to inquire as to what am I doing?

239
00:32:32,482 --> 00:32:33,805
What decisions am I making?

240
00:32:33,904 --> 00:32:43,278
What thought patterns am I constantly reproducing to create this unhappiness?

241
00:32:43,398 --> 00:32:47,625
Even if I'm doing things which are actually making me very happy

242
00:32:48,044 --> 00:33:05,711
helping people and art and going to the cinema and all the things that we can do to generate a sense of well-being and goodness within us, even that can become painful when the stuff begins to disappear or when we fall ill.

243
00:33:06,093 --> 00:33:11,300
I have a friend at the moment who likes to walk and he likes the country, likes to

244
00:33:11,280 --> 00:33:20,564
visit places and through an accident of sorts he's gone and done something to his Achilles heel or something.

245
00:33:21,025 --> 00:33:23,451
He has to hobble.

246
00:33:24,005 --> 00:33:32,333
And whenever I am in contact with him, I can see he's very frustrated with it, you know, he's very angry, and the NHS should do something about this.

247
00:33:34,234 --> 00:33:43,825
And he's finding it very difficult because it's curtailed his happiness, which was dependent on all this stuff.

248
00:33:46,807 --> 00:33:53,454
So when we really want to know about the karma, the real karma,

249
00:33:53,569 --> 00:33:58,136
which is to do with our liberation from suffering, then it's always inward.

250
00:33:58,196 --> 00:34:05,606
It's always looking inward to see exactly what it is we're doing that creates the world that we are living in.

251
00:34:06,448 --> 00:34:08,391
And that's the real thing we have to grasp.

252
00:34:09,552 --> 00:34:12,536
It doesn't deny the reality of the outside world.

253
00:34:12,577 --> 00:34:15,782
It doesn't deny the reality of other people and so on and so forth.

254
00:34:16,362 --> 00:34:19,527
But what it does say is that the world I'm living in

255
00:34:20,148 --> 00:34:21,550
is the world I'm creating.

256
00:34:22,452 --> 00:34:26,641
Even at the basic, even at that basic level of the senses, you know?

257
00:34:27,202 --> 00:34:33,255
If, I mean, if I'm colorblind, then I see things that people, other people don't see.

258
00:34:33,775 --> 00:34:36,702
And I see, I see the universe differently, right?

259
00:34:36,722 --> 00:34:38,005
Just even at that level.

260
00:34:38,844 --> 00:34:49,923
And when we recognize that, then we actually take on that responsibility, the full responsibility of trying to do something about our situation.

261
00:34:50,204 --> 00:34:51,126
And that's why we're all here.

262
00:34:51,465 --> 00:34:54,811
We wouldn't be here if we hadn't taken on that responsibility.

263
00:34:56,952 --> 00:35:02,139
Now, one thing that might be said is, oh, well, this is very selfish.

264
00:35:02,159 --> 00:35:04,744
It's very self-centered.

265
00:35:04,864 --> 00:35:10,112
It's not, you know, what about love and other people and all that?

266
00:35:10,132 --> 00:35:17,204
Well, of course, what we begin to realize is that there is this interconnectedness.

267
00:35:18,028 --> 00:35:30,333
Before, when we were reacting to people, we were reacting from some self-centeredness, some ego-centered, I don't particularly like using the word ego, but there we are.

268
00:35:30,652 --> 00:35:57,974
some selfishness, only self-regard so that everything has to fit in with what I want how the world fits in with me as we begin to undermine that of course the magic is that suddenly you begin to experience other people and the world and nature differently because this kink in the way we're looking at things has been taken away, slowly being drained out of the system

269
00:35:58,494 --> 00:36:01,617
I had a lovely incident once in a car with my parents.

270
00:36:03,400 --> 00:36:11,690
My mother was Italian and she could get a little bit depressed at times.

271
00:36:11,730 --> 00:36:15,813
And we were driving along and we hit this beautiful scenery.

272
00:36:16,775 --> 00:36:21,920
And I can't remember whether it was my brother in the car, but somebody said, oh, look at that, Mum, isn't it beautiful?

273
00:36:22,576 --> 00:36:23,617
And she says, oh, what?

274
00:36:23,677 --> 00:36:25,159
I can't see anything.

275
00:36:25,800 --> 00:36:28,706
And my father said, oh, cheer up, Rosa.

276
00:36:29,086 --> 00:36:32,132
And she said, you shut up.

277
00:36:32,152 --> 00:36:34,936
It was a brilliant little party.

278
00:36:35,456 --> 00:36:42,588
And here you've got where you completely misheard something because of her own grumpiness.

279
00:36:43,349 --> 00:36:44,431
She did cheer up, by the way.

280
00:36:46,335 --> 00:36:58,550
So you get this, every time, remember, you're in a mood, every time a mood comes up, it puts a colouring on the world, you see, puts a colouring on the world around you, and you can't stop that.

281
00:36:58,570 --> 00:37:05,177
Now that's the second thing that we come about this psychology, about the real karma, which is to do with our liberation.

282
00:37:06,199 --> 00:37:14,367
Past conditioning, you can't just get rid of, you can't just say, well, you know, I'm not going to be angry anymore, full stop, and it just doesn't work.

283
00:37:14,938 --> 00:37:18,362
what we realize is that this conditioning is not me.

284
00:37:18,682 --> 00:37:19,463
This is the funny thing.

285
00:37:19,563 --> 00:37:20,925
It's not me, it's not mine.

286
00:37:20,965 --> 00:37:25,670
I've created it through these acts of will, but it's not me, it's not mine.

287
00:37:25,710 --> 00:37:29,673
It has its own engine, it has its own power, it has its own obstinacy.

288
00:37:30,534 --> 00:37:43,106
And so what we find ourselves having to do is to sit patiently, to endure all the conditionings that we've created through these delusive thinking, delusive actions, delusive speech.

289
00:37:43,963 --> 00:37:46,867
And that's really the hard bit of the practice.

290
00:37:47,068 --> 00:38:00,766
I mean, that in a sense is why the Buddha, I think, calls them hindrances, because were it not for those, we would very quickly attain liberation, we would attain enlightenment.

291
00:38:01,487 --> 00:38:08,114
What's actually dragging us down, making it very difficult for us, is our past conditions.

292
00:38:09,125 --> 00:38:14,507
So, this demands this patient endurance that the Buddha often talks about.

293
00:38:14,929 --> 00:38:17,481
The highest form of ascetic practice is patience.

294
00:38:18,592 --> 00:38:37,309
And when we sit and we are allowing the karma, the vipāka, this is the product of past actions, the product of past decisions, the product of past karma, we are allowing it to manifest in its fullness and beginning to die out.

295
00:38:37,329 --> 00:38:45,358
And then we are changing that energy into its opposite through the practice of goodwill.

296
00:38:45,827 --> 00:39:14,215
and even if we don't do the practice of goodwill as a specific practice the fact that energy which has manifested as anger or grudges or depression all that stuff it naturally manifests outwardly begins to manifest rather in a positive way because remember what's changing in this process is our view of things and our view of things changes our relationship to things

297
00:39:14,684 --> 00:39:40,860
and therefore just by sitting with whatever negative states come up within us you see that even that is part of the process of changing our understanding of the world and finally you could say we come to that deep sort of delusion

298
00:39:41,177 --> 00:40:01,684
which is creating all this obvious karma which is the initial mistake that's also our fundamental karma in terms of liberation this fundamental mistake of seeking happiness in the sensual world

299
00:40:03,132 --> 00:40:12,085
And by sensual world we mean the whole caboodle, we mean the whole cosmos, we mean other people, we mean everything that can be felt, sensed.

300
00:40:13,586 --> 00:40:14,568
That's the sensual world.

301
00:40:15,309 --> 00:40:31,452
And by seeking real happiness there, confusing pleasure, confusing the joys of life, see the Buddha's not saying he doesn't enjoy life, he enjoys life, he enjoys the things that life brings, but confusing that with real happiness is where the problem lies.

302
00:40:32,157 --> 00:40:45,659
And that's why I say, when your meditation is very calm and you've got just a general peaceful state, and you are in that place of the observer, you just ask yourself, what is the state of the observer?

303
00:40:47,833 --> 00:41:00,413
And just to finish off, when Sariputta, you see, is asked, you talk about the bliss of Nibbāna, you talk about the joy of Nibbāna, but there's no emotions in Nibbāna.

304
00:41:00,432 --> 00:41:04,659
He says, well, it's the very absence of emotions which is the bliss of Nibbāna.

305
00:41:04,679 --> 00:41:09,927
You get your head around that one.

306
00:41:11,003 --> 00:41:16,849
The law of karma, really, in terms of the spiritual laws, which is the fifth law.

307
00:41:17,028 --> 00:41:22,092
So we had the physical laws, the biological laws, the psychic laws, psychological laws.

308
00:41:22,713 --> 00:41:27,117
The law of karma, which is the law of morality, really, the ethics.

309
00:41:28,018 --> 00:41:29,179
You know, it's ethics.

310
00:41:30,081 --> 00:41:39,610
And finally, we have this law of the spiritual laws, in which we can include our vipassana, the Four Noble Truths, and so forth.

311
00:41:41,885 --> 00:41:46,771
And so karma holds this specific place of action.

312
00:41:47,833 --> 00:41:52,039
Every time we do something, we have to remind ourselves that it's going to have some effect.

313
00:41:52,960 --> 00:41:57,226
So we have to be very careful not to get neurotic about it.

314
00:41:58,108 --> 00:42:02,474
And remember that an act of attention is an act of intention.

315
00:42:02,724 --> 00:42:04,367
That's really, really important to grab.

316
00:42:04,387 --> 00:42:07,853
As soon as you attend to something, there's an act of intention there.

317
00:42:09,193 --> 00:42:19,550
So, every time you're sitting on a bus and you're passing these billboards and you look at them, you know, and you attend to them, it's affecting you.

318
00:42:19,690 --> 00:42:20,570
It's a passive state.

319
00:42:20,650 --> 00:42:23,114
We're not doing it on purpose, but it's going in.

320
00:42:23,996 --> 00:42:29,204
Because to put your attention somewhere demands an act of intention.

321
00:42:31,126 --> 00:42:32,108
So,

322
00:42:32,931 --> 00:42:40,244
So our aim is to keep pointing our attention at what is wholesome, what is good for us.

323
00:42:40,764 --> 00:42:48,797
And eventually, you know, I'm sure you've all felt a turning, a movement within yourself.

324
00:43:08,065 --> 00:43:11,175
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

325
00:43:11,195 --> 00:43:24,943
May you be liberated from all your karma and achieve full liberation sooner rather than later.

